The paper deals with a nonnegative matrix factorization problem and proposes a modification to the successive projection algorithm to enhance its noise robustness. This problem is commonly studied in the machine learning and data science communities, which fall under the cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the computational cost of the algorithm and proposes a modification to address it, which falls under the cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) sub-category. Additionally, the paper presents an empirical study to evaluate the performance of the proposed algorithm, which falls under the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-categories.
